  "ap-calculus": {
    id: "ap-calculus", title: "AP Calculus (AB/BC)",
    description: "Practice for AP Calculus AB and BC. Covers limits, derivatives, integrals, and their applications.",
    category: "academic",
    questions: [
      { q: "What is the derivative of f(x) = x³ − 4x + 2?",
        options: ["3x² − 4", "x² − 4", "3x² + 2", "3x³ − 4x"],
        answer: 0,
        explanation: "Power rule: d/dx[xⁿ] = nxⁿ⁻¹. So d/dx[x³] = 3x², d/dx[−4x] = −4, d/dx[2] = 0. Answer: 3x² − 4." },
      { q: "What is ∫ 3x² dx?",
        options: ["6x + C", "x³ + C", "9x³ + C", "x² + C"],
        answer: 1,
        explanation: "Power rule for integration: ∫xⁿ dx = xⁿ⁺¹/(n+1) + C. ∫3x² dx = 3 · x³/3 + C = x³ + C." },
      { q: "What is lim(x→0) (sin x) / x?",
        options: ["0", "∞", "undefined", "1"],
        answer: 3,
        explanation: "This is a foundational limit in calculus. lim(x→0) sin(x)/x = 1. It can be proved geometrically using the squeeze theorem and is essential for differentiating sine." },
      { q: "Geometrically, what does the derivative f'(a) represent?",
        options: ["The area under the curve at x = a", "The slope of the tangent line to f at x = a", "The average value of f on [0, a]", "The concavity of f at x = a"],
        answer: 1,
        explanation: "The derivative at a point gives the instantaneous rate of change — geometrically, the slope of the tangent line at that point. The second derivative tells us concavity." },
      { q: "State the Chain Rule for differentiating f(g(x)):",
        options: ["f'(x) + g'(x)", "f(g'(x))", "f'(g(x)) · g'(x)", "f'(x) · g'(x)"],
        answer: 2,
        explanation: "The Chain Rule: d/dx[f(g(x))] = f'(g(x)) · g'(x). Example: d/dx[sin(x²)] = cos(x²) · 2x. It's essential for differentiating composite functions." }
    ]
  },

